trated News of Montreal, 7 July 1883 obituary"},{"label":"FindAGrave #108974157","url":"https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/108974157/nathaniel_stevens-whitney"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD0584","date_year":1847,"date_month":7,"date_day":27,"location_city":"Montréal","location_state":"Quebec","location_country":"Canada","end_type":"death","end_year":1883,"children_ids":["HD4211","HD4212","HD4213","HD4214","HD4215","HD4216","HD4217","HD4218"]}],"parents":{"father_research_notes":"Family was United Empire Loyalist stock per the 1883 Canadian Illustrated News obituary — refugees from the American Revolution who fled north to British Canada. Not built per Jalapeño Rule."},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["business","civic"],"notable_blurb":"Montreal merchant, Telegraph Co founder, Horticultural Society president","primary_url":"https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/108974157/nathaniel_stevens-whitney","primary_url_label":"FindAGrave memorial #108974157"},"birth":{"year":1820,"month":12,"day":2,"city":"Frelighsburg","county":"Estrie Region","state":"Quebec","country":"Canada"},"death":{"year":1883,"month":6,"day":2,"city":"Montréal","state":"Quebec","country":"Canada"},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Nathaniel Stevens Whitney","first_name":"Nathaniel","last_name":"Whitney","middle_name":"Stevens","married_names":[],"gender":"male","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1778703800/nathanielwhitney_yh465n.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait of Nathaniel Stevens Whitney (1820-1883), Montreal merchant and civic leader."},"residence":{"city":"Montréal","state":"Quebec","country":"Canada"},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[{"text":"Another of Montreal's worthies, the esteemed and widely-beloved gentleman, Nathaniel S. Whitney, has at last gone over to the majority at the comparatively early age of 62 years. Respected by all alike, for his loving and excellent qualities, he will long be missed, and his death leaves a blank in a large circle which will not soon be filled up.","source":"Canadian Illustrated News of Montreal, July 7, 1883","date":"1883-07-07","notes":"Obituary excerpt for Nathaniel Stevens Whitney."}],"military_service":[{"war":"Rebellions of 1837-1838","war_id":"WAR015","rank_year_start":1837,"rank_year_end":1838,"notes":"Served in both winters of the Rebellions of 1837-1838 (Lower Canada Rebellion), although not of the age required by law (he was only 17 in 1837). Per the Canadian Illustrated News: 'showed himself a worthy descendant [of United Empire Loyalist stock] by serving in both winters of the rebellion, although not of the age required by law.'"}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM328","plot_notes":"Cimetière Mont-Royal Montreal — Mr. Whitney was himself a trustee of the cemetery."},"career":[{"role":"Wholesale dry goods merchant","organization":"Whitney & Co (Montreal)","location":"Montréal","notes":"Entered wholesale dry goods business after moving to Montreal at an early age from Frelighsburg."},{"role":"Leather merchant","organization":"Montreal","location":"Montréal","end_year":1883,"notes":"Subsequently entered the leather business, in which he continued until his death."},{"role":"Founding figure","organization":"Montreal Telegraph Company","location":"Montréal","notes":"The first meeting of the Montreal Telegraph Company at its organization was held in his office — placing him at the founding of one of the earliest Canadian telecommunications enterprises."},{"role":"President","organization":"Montreal Horticultural Society","location":"Montréal","end_year":1883,"notes":"Largely instrumental in forming the Montreal Horticultural Society, of which he was latterly president."},{"role":"Life Governor","organization":"Montreal General Hospital","location":"Montréal","end_year":1883,"notes":"Life Governor 'not in name only, but in deeds and activity, as the annual reports have testified' per the Canadian Illustrated News obituary."},{"role":"Trustee","organization":"Mount Royal Cemetery","location":"Montréal","end_year":1883,"notes":"Trustee of the Mount Royal Cemetery — where he himself would be buried in 1883."},{"role":"Lay delegate to Synod / Governor of Diocesan College","organization":"Church of England (Anglican Church of Canada)","location":"Montréal","end_year":1883,"notes":"Devoted adherent of the Church of England. Lay delegate to the Synod for many years; member of the executive committee; Governor of the Diocesan College."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"business","header":"Telegraph Company founded in his Montreal office","body":"Nathaniel Stevens Whitney came to Montreal at an early age from Frelighsburg Quebec and entered the wholesale dry goods business, subsequently the leather trade, which he continued until his death. The first meeting of the Montreal Telegraph Company at its organization was held in his office — placing him at the founding of one of the earliest Canadian telecommunications enterprises. He was instrumental in founding the Montreal Horticultural Society and served as its latter-day president."},{"number":2,"category":"civic","header":"Life governor MGH, Mount Royal Cemetery trustee","body":"Whitney was Life Governor of the Montreal General Hospital — not in name only but in deeds and activity, as the annual reports testified — and a trustee of Mount Royal Cemetery, where he himself would eventually be buried. A devoted Anglican, he served for many years as lay delegate to the Synod, executive committee member, and Governor of the Diocesan College. Several times invited to stand as Liberal candidate for his native county, he always declined."},{"number":3,"category":"military","header":"Rebellion veteran underage, UEL stock","body":"Of United Empire Loyalist stock, Whitney served in both winters of the Rebellions of 1837-1838 at Lower Canada — although he was only seventeen in 1837 and not of the age required by law. He caught the cold resulting in his death while visiting The Hills, his country residence at Frelighsburg where he kept a large stock farm. The Canadian Illustrated News obituary of July 7, 1883 called him 'another of Montreal's worthies, the esteemed and widely-beloved gentleman.'"}],"slug":"nathaniel-whitney-1820"},"HD0584":{"id":"HD0584","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":8,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1826,"month":11,"day":16,"city":"Montréal","state":"Lower Canada (Quebec)","country":"Canada"},"death":{"year":1905,"month":1,"day":3},"parents":{"mother_id":"HD0581","father_research_notes":"Mayor John Easton Mills","father_id":"X01251"},"tags":["canada_migration"],"sources":[],"gender":"female","marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X01591","date_year":1847,"date_month":7,"date_day":27,"location_city":"Montréal","location_state":"Quebec","location_country":"Canada","end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1883,"children_ids":["HD4211","HD4212","HD4213","HD4214","HD4215","HD4216","HD4217","HD4218"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Hannah Jane Mills Whitney","first_name":"Hannah","last_name":"Whitney","middle_name":"Jane","maiden_name":"Mills","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1778703636/hannahmillswhitney-resized_imklgp.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait of Hannah Jane Mills Whitney (1826-1905)."},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM328","plot_notes":"Mount Royal Cemetery Montreal."},"slug":"hannah-whitney-1826"},"X01251":{"id":"X01251","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":["politician","epidemic_death","canada_migration"],"sources":[{"label":"Wikipedia — John Easton Mills","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Easton_Mills"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD0581","date_year":1826,"date_month":1,"date_day":14,"location_city":"Montréal","location_state":"Quebec","location_country":"Canada","end_type":"death","end_year":1847,"children_ids":["HD0584","HD4184","HD4185","HD4186","HD0585","HD0586"]}],"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["politics"],"notable_blurb":"Montreal mayor died of typhus tending Irish immigrants","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Easton_Mills","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia — John Easton Mills"},"birth":{"year":1796,"month":10,"day":14,"city":"Tolland Center","county":"Hampden County","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1847,"month":11,"day":12,"city":"Montréal","state":"Quebec","country":"Canada","cause":"typhus"},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"John Easton Mills","first_name":"John","last_name":"Mills","middle_name":"Easton","married_names":[],"gender":"male","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1778701121/John_Easton_Mills_k5mmnt.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait of John Easton Mills (1796-1847), Mayor of Montreal."},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM328","plot_notes":"Cimetière Mont-Royal Montreal — Plot Section G2, Number G204."},"career":[{"role":"Mayor of Montreal","organization":"City of Montreal","location":"Montréal","start_year":1846,"end_year":1847,"notes":"Elected December 1846 after a deadlocked March 1846 council vote (Mills 10, incumbent James Ferrier 9 — Ferrier voted for himself twice per existing rules; municipal paralysis ensued until December 1846 when Mills was elected decisively). Less than one year in office before his death from typhus November 12, 1847."},{"role":"Merchant","organization":"Montreal","location":"Montréal","end_year":1846,"notes":"Prominent Montreal merchant prior to election as mayor."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"death","header":"Mayor caught typhus tending Irish famine immigrants","body":"John Easton Mills was elected Mayor of Montreal in December 1846 after months of deadlock on the city council. Less than a year into his term, the 1847 typhus outbreak struck Montreal among Irish famine immigrants. He personally organized containment measures and volunteered to tend the sick in the Pointe-Saint-Charles immigrant fever sheds — contracted typhus himself — and died November 12, 1847 after less than one year in office."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Three of his sons died in 1841","body":"George at six, Edwin at two, and the infant Albert all died in 1841 — likely an epidemic year inside the household. His daughter Ada would die six decades later at the center of Montreal’s Redpath Mansion Mystery."}],"slug":"john-mills-1796"},"HD0581":{"id":"HD0581","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1799,"month":9,"day":20,"city":"Derby","county":"Orleans County","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1881,"month":5,"day":7,"city":"Norwood","country":"England"},"parents":{"mother_id":"H00463","father_research_notes":"Elisha Lyman","father_id":"X01250"},"tags":["canada_migration"],"sources":[],"marriages":[{"children_ids":["HD0584","HD4184","HD4185","HD4186","HD0585","HD0586"],"spouse_id":"X01251","marriage_number":1,"date_year":1826,"date_month":1,"date_day":14,"location_city":"Montreal","location_state":"Lower Canada"}],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Hannah Lyman","first_name":"Hannah","maiden_name":"Lyman","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Married Montreal mayor who died caring for immigrants","body":"Hannah Lyman married John Easton Mills January 14, 1826 in Montreal. Her husband became Mayor of Montreal and died in 1847 of typhus contracted while personally caring for Irish famine immigrants in the city's fever sheds. She survived him by thirty-four years, eventually dying at Norwood near London England at age eighty-one in 1881."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Three sons all died in single 1841 year","body":"Hannah Lyman Mills lost three of her sons in 1841: George at age six, Edwin at age two, and Albert in infancy. The pattern suggests a single epidemic or catastrophic event swept through the Mills household that year. She would lose her husband John Easton Mills to typhus six years later, leaving her with three daughters who all married into the Montreal mercantile elite."}],"slug":"hannah-lyman-1799"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM328","name":"Cimetière Mont-Royal","city":"Outremont","state":"Montréal Region","country":"Canada","founded":1852,"wikipedia_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Royal_Cemetery","primary_url":"https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/639448/cimeti%C3%A8re-mont-royal","hooker_connections":["HD0580","HD0583","HD0584","HD0585","HD0586","HD0587","HD0588","HD4178","HD4182","HD4183","HD4187","HD4188","HD4189","HD4190","HD4191","HD4192","HD4194","HD4196","HD4198","HD4199","HD4210","HD4211","HD4213","HD4214","HD4219","HD4220","HD4221","HD4228","HD4229","I00630","I00631","I00632","I00634","I00640","I00641","I00643","I00645","I00646","I00647","X01250","X01251","X01252","X01253","X01591","X02825","I01230"],"notes":"Cimetière Mont-Royal (Mount Royal Cemetery), Outremont, Montreal QC. Major Protestant cemetery founded 1852 on the slopes of Mount Royal. Burial site of multiple members of the Lyman family — Hannah Stiles Lyman's descendants who became prominent Montreal druggists, lawyers, and civic figures: Elisha Lyman Jr. (with his three wives memorialized together), Henry Lyman, Mary Corse Lyman, Henry Herbert Lyman (later commemorated here after death on the Empress of Ireland 1914), Albert Clarence Lyman, Frederick Stiles Lyman, Edith Mary Louise Lyman, and others."},"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}